# Level-shifter skeleton (std.elec.patterns.LevelShifter, WO-53). Fill
# in the low/high-side rail voltages; `regolith doc` renders the
# pattern's datasheet (ports, spec law, promises, citations).
#
# HONEST ENGINE GAP (verified empirically, WO-53 template audit):
# instantiating ANY pattern generic (`LevelShifter<...=free, ...>`
# here) emits an unresolved `conforms` obligation that
# `orchestrator/translate.py` always defers with
# `conformance_windows_unresolved` -- refinement-bound extraction for
# pattern generics is a named WO-12 engine cut, not specific to this
# template. `regolith build --release` / `regolith ship` therefore
# cannot succeed for ANY `level_shifter`-scaffolded project until
# WO-12 lands, regardless of what other claims the file carries.
import std.elec.patterns (LevelShifter)

board TranslatorBoard:
    parts:
        shifter: LevelShifter<v_lo=free, v_hi=free>

    # Second, clearly-marked claim (independent of the pattern above): a
    # real, honestly-dischargeable rail check, so the discharge machinery
    # and build report stay meaningful even though the overall release
    # gate is blocked by the WO-12 gap noted above. vout ~= 3.33V for
    # these numbers, comfortably inside the window.
    loads:
        vin: [5.0, 5.0]
        r1: [10000, 10000]
        r2: [25000, 25000]
        rload: [100000, 100000]

    require Power:
        elec.rail.lo: >= 3.2
        elec.rail.hi: <= 3.4
